Certainly! Below is a simple HTML web app that generates random closed curves resembling fried eggs in yellow and white. The app uses HTML5 Canvas for drawing and some embedded CSS and JavaScript to manage the functionality. You can simply copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in your browser:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Fried Eggs Generator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        canvas {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
        button {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<canvas id="friedEggCanvas" width="600" height="400"></canvas>
<button id="generateButton">Generate Fried Eggs</button>

<script>
    function drawFriedEgg(context, x, y) {
        const whiteWidth = Math.random() * 100 + 30; // Random white part width
        const whiteHeight = Math.random() * 50 + 20; // Random white part height
        const yolkRadius = Math.random() * 25 + 10; // Random yolk size

        // Draw the white part of the egg
        context.beginPath();
        context.ellipse(x, y, whiteWidth, whiteHeight, Math.random() * Math.PI, 0, 2 * Math.PI);
        context.fillStyle = 'white';
        context.fill();
        context.closePath();

        // Draw the yolk
        context.beginPath();
        context.arc(x, y, yolkRadius, 0, 2 * Math.PI);
        context.fillStyle = 'yellow';
        context.fill();
        context.closePath();
    }

    function generateFriedEggs() {
        const canvas = document.getElementById('friedEggCanvas');
        const context = canvas.getContext('2d');
        context.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height); // Clear canvas

        const eggCount = Math.floor(Math.random() * 5) + 1; // Random number of eggs (1 to 5)
        for (let i = 0; i < eggCount; i++) {
            const x = Math.random() * canvas.width; // Random x position
            const y = Math.random() * canvas.height; // Random y position
            drawFriedEgg(context, x, y);
        }
    }

    document.getElementById('generateButton').addEventListener('click', generateFriedEggs);
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Open a text editor (like Notepad, VSCode, etc.).
3. Paste the code into a new file.
4. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `fried_eggs.html`).
5. Open the saved file in any web browser.

### Features:
- The canvas will display randomly generated "fried eggs" each time you click the "Generate Fried Eggs" button.
- Each egg has a uniquely sized white part and yolk, creating a randomized "fried egg" effect.
